</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,222,319]" pageId="9" pageNumber="326">
The species is redescribed and illustrated in the unpublished thesis of 
<bibRefCitation author="Serra-Tosio" box="[1011,1247,222,247]" pageId="9" pageNumber="326" refString="Serra-Tosio, B. (1971 b) Contribution l'etude taxonomique, phylogenetique, biogeo-graphique et ecologique des Diamesini (Diptera, Chironomidae) d'Europe, These Universite Scientific et Medicale de Grenoble, 1, 1 - 303; 2, 304 - 462. P 1, 1 - 184." type="journal article" year="1971" yearSuffix="b">Serra-Tosio (1971b)</bibRefCitation>
. The species is coldstenothermal (
<bibRefCitation author="Marziali" box="[362,663,258,283]" pageId="9" pageNumber="326" refString="Marziali, L. &amp; Rossaro, B. (2013) Quantitative response of Chironomid species to water temperature: effects on species distribution in specific habitats. Journal of Entomological and Acarological Research, 45 e 14, 73 - 89. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4081 / jear. 2013. e 14" type="journal article" year="2013">Marziali &amp; Rossaro 2013</bibRefCitation>
) and one of the commonest species in glacial habitat (
<bibRefCitation author="Rossaro" pageId="9" pageNumber="326" refString="Rossaro, B. &amp; Lencioni, V. (2015 a) A key to larvae of species belonging to the genus Diamesa. European Journal Environmental Sciences, 5, 62 - 79." type="journal article" year="2015" yearSuffix="a">Rossaro &amp; Lencioni 2015a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rossaro" box="[340,357,294,319]" pageId="9" pageNumber="326" refString="Rossaro, B. &amp; Lencioni, V. (2015 b) A Key to Larvae of Diamesa Meigen, 1835 (Diptera, Chironomidae), well known as adult males and pupae from Alps (Europe) Journal of Entomological and Acarological Research, 47, 123 - 138." type="journal article" year="2015" yearSuffix="b">b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
